{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658465"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:48:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:48:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20753"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20753"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.18,0.23,0.05,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13628"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95673"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13628"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20753"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78474"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11657"},{"type":"tags","id":"12452"},{"type":"tags","id":"12473"},{"type":"tags","id":"12617"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32773"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95673"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with weakness, numbness, and tingling in her extremities, abdominal pain, and diarrhoea. Examination shows hyperpigmentation on her palms and soles with hyperkeratosis. She drinks water from a private well in a rural area.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiological mechanism of this patient\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Interference with mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation","Competitive inhibition of selenium-dependent enzymes","Antibody-mediated destruction of peripheral nerves","Inhibition of nucleotide excision repair pathways","Direct stimulation of keratinocyte proliferation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with chronic arsenic toxicity, likely from contaminated groundwater. The primary pathophysiological mechanism involves \u003Cstrong\u003Einterference with mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation\u003C/strong\u003E. Trivalent arsenic compounds can replace phosphates in ATP, disrupting cellular energy production and affecting multiple organ systems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of nucleotide excision repair pathways\u003C/strong\u003E - While this may contribute to arsenic\u0027s carcinogenic effects, it is not the primary mechanism causing the acute and subacute toxicities described in this case.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetitive inhibition of selenium-dependent enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - This is more characteristic of mercury toxicity rather than arsenic poisoning.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect stimulation of keratinocyte proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E - Arsenic causes hyperkeratosis through toxicity to keratinocytes, not by direct stimulation of their proliferation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibody-mediated destruction of peripheral nerves\u003C/strong\u003E - Arsenic causes direct toxic damage to peripheral nerves, not an immune-mediated process.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArsenic toxicity manifests with multiple system involvement including:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENeurological effects: sensorimotor neuropathy causing paresthesias, numbness, and pain\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGastrointestinal effects: abdominal pain and diarrhoea\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECardiovascular effects: hypertension and arrhythmias\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDermatological effects: hyperpigmentation and hyperkeratosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic exposure also increases the risk of cancers, particularly of the skin, lung, and bladder. The skin tumors associated with arsenic exposure often appear on the palms and soles, unlike those induced by ultraviolet radiation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Arsenic toxicity affects multiple organ systems including the gastrointestinal tract, nervous system, skin, and heart.","Chronic arsenic exposure causes characteristic skin changes including hyperpigmentation and hyperkeratosis.","Arsenic increases cancer risk, particularly in the skin, lung, and bladder.","Trivalent arsenic compounds are the most toxic forms and can interfere with mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 9; page 413."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78474"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20753"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78474"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-28T23:33:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-28T23:34:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13628"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95673"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCo